^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, the bidding was fine. It is very difficult for Kerrie to guess the K of hearts is singleton. But, let us discuss "coded 10s and 9s." First of all, they only apply in NT contracts, not suit contracts. So, in this contract, coded 9s do not apply. Secondly, let us take the lead of the 10 first.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If playing coded 10s, and you lead the 10, it means one of two things: (a) you have a sequence headed by the 10 with nothing higher (e.g. 1098x) or (b) you have a broken sequence with the J10 (e.g. AJ109x KJ108x). Some people say it shows "zero or two higher." That is correct but not a sufficient explanation.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|For example, suppose you have the suit AQ10x. If you use the "2 higher" rule, you should lead the 10. However, that is not the correct lead. The "x" is the correct lead. So, coded 10s shows either none higher or (2) a broken sequence with the J10. In this fashion, if you play coded 10s, the lead of the J denies a higher honor--if partner leads the Jack, he has J109 or J108 and neither the Ace or the King. That is useful information. If he leads the 10, you can usually work out if he has zero or two higher, and what the higher one is.|
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Coded 9s work similarly. The lead of the 9 shows one of two things; (1)either nothing higher than the 9 (e.g. 98xx) or a broken sequence with the 10 (e.g. A109x K109x or Q109x). So, even if we were playing coded 9s, Eddy's suit is not suitable for a coded 9 lead.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


AT|
EddyHaskel: Are coded 9 or 10s led only from five or can they be led from four?|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|You can lead from 4, but in that case I would make sure you have J109 or J108 or 1098 or 1097 in your suit.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, as to why they are not played in suits. Because you are less likely to make that lead in a suit. You would never lead away from an Ace, so that already eliminates 2 possibilities and you are less likely to lead away from KJ, K10, or Q10. So, there is not much point in playing them.|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT|^B@2
EddyHaskel: Why is 9 as top of interior sequence wrong?|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Because then you cannot distinguish whether or not partner has a higher honor.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


AT|
esprit12: Are coded 10s & 9s leads only refer to opening lead?|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Yes, they only apply to the opening lead. Once you are in the middle of the hand, the distribution of the cards is usually clearer.|
