HT|H|cp|5|FP||AT|
^c@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Once the Blackwood bidder receives a response to 4N, he may then bid 5N as a king ask. There are two variations to the K response. The variation I have a preference for is to respond with the number of kings (obviously not counting the K of trumps).|
PG| ***** 171 ***** |


AT|

- 6@C = 0 kings, 
- 6@D = 1 king, 
- 6@H = 2 kings, 
- 6@S = 3 kings. |
PG| ***** 172 ***** |


AT|

The other variation is "specific kings". If you play that, then you respond with the cheapest suit in which you have an outside K; if you do not have an outside K, you bid six in the agreed upon trump suit. |
PG| ***** 173 ***** |


AT|

The main complication playing specific kings is if your specific king is in a suit higher than the agreed upon trump suit. I play that you should respond with your specific king even in that case (partner needs to be prepared for that response), but some people play you can only respond with a specific king if it is in a suit lower than your agreed upon trump suit.|
PG| ***** 174 ***** |


AT|

Also, most people play that if the Blackwood bidder bids 5N as a king ask, that guarantees your side has all 5 key cards. That allows the responder, on rare occasions, to bid seven if he has a hand with an undisclosed feature that will most likely allow seven to make (such as a long solid side suit, which will generate many tricks).|
PG| ***** 175 ***** |


AT|

Let us look at an example.|
